# Project Overview

## Stack
- **GOV.UK Prototype Kit** (Node.js, Express)
- **Nunjucks** for server-rendered templates
- **GOV.UK Frontend** components and design system
- **Custom mapping** (Leaflet, GeoJSON, turf.js) for red line boundary and EDP layers

## Purpose
Rapid prototyping of user journeys for the Nature Restoration Fund (NRF) levy service. Prototypes demonstrate user flows, form patterns, and map-based boundary capture; focus is on UX and flow over production security.

## Directory Structure

```
app/
├── config/
│   ├── shared/
│   │   ├── journeys.js          # JOURNEYS list; used by app and tests
│   │   └── building-types.js     # Shared building type config
│   └── {journey-name}/          # Per-journey route constants
│       └── routes.js            # ROUTES and TEMPLATES
├── routes/
│   ├── routes.js                # Main router; mounts journey routes from JOURNEYS
│   ├── index.js
│   ├── nrf-estimate-4.js        # One route file per journey (by base path)
│   ├── lpa-approve-2.js
│   └── ...
├── views/
│   ├── layouts/
│   │   └── main.html
│   └── {journey-name}/          # One folder per journey; one HTML per page
│       ├── start.html
│       ├── what-would-you-like-to-do.html
│       └── ...
├── lib/                         # Shared validators, helpers (e.g. nrf-estimate-3)
├── assets/
│   └── map-layers/              # GeoJSON for EDP boundaries, catchments
└── data/                        # Optional journey-specific data modules
```

## Journey Configuration
- Journeys are defined in `app/config/shared/journeys.js` as `JOURNEYS`.
- Each entry has `name`, `displayName`, `basePath` (e.g. `/nrf-estimate-4`), optional `hasStartPage`, `entryPath`, `description`.
- Add a new journey by adding an entry to `JOURNEYS` and creating `app/routes/{basePathWithoutSlash}.js` (e.g. `nrf-estimate-4.js`). `app/routes.js` loads route modules dynamically from `JOURNEYS`, so no change to `routes.js` is needed for new journeys.
- **Completeness**: For every journey, ensure (1) an entry exists in `JOURNEYS`, (2) `app/config/{journey}/routes.js` exists on disk if `app/routes/{journey}.js` requires it, and (3) `node -e "require('./app/routes/{journey}.js')"` succeeds from the repo root. Omitting (1) or (2) typically causes **404** for the whole journey (router never mounts).

## Key Principles
- **User journey first**: Implement flows from prompts (page flow, data points, content, errors).
- **Session for prototype data**: Use `req.session.data` for form and journey state; no production persistence.
- **GOV.UK Design System**: Use GOV.UK Frontend components and content guidelines; British English.

